1119363315124150272.text:
Special delivery! 

Our flying robotic “bees” arrived earlier today at the @Space_Station. If you haven’t heard about our Astrobee robots , here’s what all the buzz is about: http://go.nasa.gov/2GtCXdx pic.twitter.com/nPhOYGTLwN

1119365239974182912.text: The robots can operate in either fully automated mode or under remote control  by astronauts or researchers on .pic.twitter.com/Iu7wgWCZu5

1119364942832922624.text: Astrobee is battery powered. When its  runs low, the robot will autonomously navigate and dock to a power station to recharge .pic.twitter.com/LbshF7eLQL

1119363702497501185.text: Before launching to space , the Astrobee robots were tested inside a special lab at @NASAAmes where researchers created a mockup of the space station’s interior.pic.twitter.com/K2RxDuexaA

1119364039455326208.text: The robots are propelled by fans. They can move in any direction  and turn on any axis  in space.pic.twitter.com/Q7QHF395eF

1119364329269153792.text: Each robot is equipped with cameras  and sensors for navigating  inside the space station and avoiding obstacles.pic.twitter.com/yH3sl1Ftkh

1119379458295623680.text:
A whole new world!  

Astronomers using data from our planet-hunting @NASAKepler space telescope have discovered a third planet orbiting two stars located approximately 3,340 light-years away! Meet the new planet, dubbed Kepler-47d: https://go.nasa.gov/2ZpGL78 pic.twitter.com/7G40OrDp5E

1119364567438544896.text: Claw power! Astrobees have a robotic arm  that can be attached for handling cargo or running experiments.pic.twitter.com/UXPM3QMvjr

1119365557524938752.text: Astrobee builds on the success of SPHERES, our first-generation robotic assistant  that arrived at the space station in 2006.pic.twitter.com/rRIEt26HWf
